pageSummary: To walk, run, cycle around the world in 80 days! because they are BAM's National Charity for 2021!!
pageSummaryWhat: To walk, run, cycle around the world in 80 days!
pageSummaryWhy: they are BAM's National Charity for 2021!!
story:
Thanks for visiting our page. 

In the current lockdown, it is unlikely that anyone is going to actually travel the world! However, between us, we could follow in the footsteps of Phileas Fogg and travel the 24,901-mile distance around the world in just 80 days!

Our aim is to each average 2.5 miles per day - roughly 5,000 steps - by either walking, running, riding, skating, hopping, scooting, or other similar method, for 80 days

We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation and we would be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. 

£24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

pageSummary: We're walking in memory of Gordon Smith because it's a great way to remember him positively.
pageSummaryWhat: We're walking in memory of Gordon Smith
pageSummaryWhy: it's a great way to remember him positively.
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit ourJustGiving page and if you're donating for a particular person, please include their name in your comment.

Gordon's Walk was created in 2019, when a group of Gordon's family, friends and colleagues climbed Pen y Fan, to celebrate his life and to promote physical and mental health and wellbeing, particularly in the face of bereavement. Afterwards, the general feeling was that people wanted to make it an annual thing! 

Last years walk had to change due to the pandemic, but we still had  21 participants, taking part safely at a social distance in 3 different locations. This year, we are planning to use the stunning Rhossilli Circular walk that we had to abandon last year, but we do have a back up plan, just in case!

To sign up for the walk or to find out more information, please email GordonsWalkBHF@gmail.com for details or message via the Facebook page at www.facebook.com/GordonsWalk.

You'll receive a t-shirt and we'll provide plenty of information, advice and encouragement to help your preparation and fundraising in the run up to the event.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Thank you for your support!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Paul was suddenly taken from us on the 28th of December after becoming unwell at home over the Christmas period. Family, friends and colleagues are invited to make a donation to the British Heart Foundation. 

The British Heart Foundation's mission is to end heartbreak from heart and circulatory diseases.

Paul was a hardworking and successful salesman for over 40 years. He loved his work and had so many wonderful colleagues and customers. He was well known and respected throughout the North West where he lived and worked throughout his whole life. 

He was a devoted brother and uncle and was also devoted to his two lovely cats Daisy and Tiger, who like the rest of us are struggling to make sense of what has happened.  

Paul's service is being held at ST Anne's Church at 10:30am on Friday the 22nd of January 2021. All donations made in his memory will be gratefully received with much love and heartfelt thanks.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Myself and two friends are doing the  North Coast 500  a 516-mile (830 km) scenic route around the north coast of Scotland, starting and ending at inverness. We plan to complete the route in 5 days in which we will be camping  out each night.

The reason for doing the challenge is to raise awareness for The British heart foundation which is a charity close to my heart.

Several years ago we lost our nephew Matthew peter Macdonald to a heart condition  early on in his short life, so we would like to take this opportunity to raise as much as we can for the charity.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
pageSummary: We are raising money because It is a charity close to my heart and many others
pageSummaryWhy: It is a charity close to my heart and many others
story: Hey guys, Friends had a really good idea for Valentines Day this year as we are probably still going to be in a lockdown.  As most of us know, February is national heart month and the British Heart Foundation is a charity close to my heart particularly and some of yours. They had the idea to raise money during Valentine’s Day and asked me to help so we came up with the idea that if you do a meal from home whether it’s a dine in for £10 or £12 or you buy different things and make a meal, order a takeaway. You round that up to the nearest 10 and donate that to the BHF this year. So for example, if you do M&S dine in (which I think is £10) you donate £10 to the BHF. If you want to join then you’re more than welcome, or you can just donate every little helps!

pageSummary: A chocaholic raising money because now is a great time to do something positive!
pageSummaryWhy: now is a great time to do something positive!
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Now, of all times, is the time to show generosity by helping save others' lives as well achieve a goal of our own!

pageSummary: Raising money because It’s a great cause
story: My story..... 2020 was the best year of my life because my beautiful perfect daughter was born!! But I know 2020 was a terrible year for a lot of people, especially charities!! My little girl was born weighing a massive 9lb3 so I went from a small 9 1/2 stone to ENORMOUS!!! So losing a few chins and raising money for a great causing sounds good! This will be extremely hard for me as I’m a complete chocoholic and don’t usually go a day without it 😱 so this event sounded like a double win to get rid of some chins!!! If you can help out with a few pennies that would be wonderful 💞Thank you 💞

pageSummary: I am fundraising because it's a good cause and I need improve my diet
pageSummaryWhy: it's a good cause and I need improve my diet
story:
Anybody who knows me will also know that at any time my body is about 34% Dairy Milk chocolate. On the eve of my 47th birthday I've decided that I should sort it out and ditch chocolate so that I can live a longer, healthier and happier life.

Almost by accident I came across this campaign so I thought I'd sign up and help somebody else whilst helping myself.

If you donate I WILL stick to the rules. No chocolate, sweets or fizzy drinks for the WHOLE of MARCH.

Please only donate if you have the means to do so - I'm not worried about hitting a specific target, I'm more concerned with making a lifestyle change in a fun way.

Thanks for reading,

James x

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

pageSummary: I have decided to give up chocolate and sweets!! because Charities need all the help they can get right now
pageSummaryWhat: I have decided to give up chocolate and sweets!!
pageSummaryWhy: Charities need all the help they can get right now
story:
Once again I have decided to take part in the British heart foundation's "Dechox". I completed it February a few years ago, and it felt amazing knowing I had helped out this great charity. 

To try and make it even harder for myself, This time I am going 1 step further... I am giving up all chocolate and sweets for the whole of March. I know it doesn't sound like a great deal, but for those who know me, will know that chocolate and sweets are my weakness! So please, your support and encouragement will be needed!! and if you can any donations would be greatly appreciated. I have set myself a target of £100 this year instead of the generic £75 that is automatically set up. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers.  We all know someone who has either been directly or indirectly affected by heart disease, whether it be heart attack, stroke and any other sort of disease, so please for the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now. 

- thank you

Hannah x

pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate in March because BHF has helped me & my dad with heart problems.
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate in March
pageSummaryWhy: BHF has helped me & my dad with heart problems.
story:
When I was three years old it was discovered that I had a heart murmur (hole in the heart) - this was something I was born with but was only discovered when I had a medical check up. After diagnosis I had to have a cardiac catheter put in to close up the hole (I have had this tiny piece of metal in my heart for nearly 21 years). Without the research of The British Heart Foundation this may not have been possible.

Also, in 2017 my dad at 60 years old had a heart attack and had to have stents fitted. All was well until just over a week later he suffered a cardiac arrest due to scar tissue on the heart due to the stents being fitted (it's very rare!). He was brought back to life by my mum and paramedics and rushed to hospital. But, a day later he suffered another cardiac arrest and was brought back to life..yet again. It was then decided he should have an ICD (Implantable Cardioverter Defibrillator) fitted to prevent anymore. It's been nearly three years since all this happened and I am happy to say he is perfectly fine. Yet again without the great research BHF does it could have been a totally different story.

So, as you can see British Heart Foundation is a charity very close to my heart and one that I want to give back too. As a chocoholic this is going to be a tough challenge but one that I will give my all to!

Any donations big or small would be appreciated :)

pageSummary: I am going to give up chocolate AND sweets because I want to raise LOTS!!!
pageSummaryWhat: I am going to give up chocolate AND sweets
story:
so i received an email about ‘Dechox’ to raise money to help the British Heart Foundation, this is because I done it a few years ago.....

Well, i do love a challenge!!!! Most know my dad sadly died in November 2020, this was due to Coronary Heart Disease which led to Heart Failure, he had a triple heart bypass in 2010, as we very nearly lost him then, thankfully we had him for 10 more years.  I would love to smash my target and help this amazing charity as it means a lot to me.

Also by giving up not only CHOCOLATE (which i love) I am ALSO giving up ALL SWEETS......this will not be an easy task, definitely a challenge but I am up for it!

PLEASE sponsor me, even £1 would be amazing, and remember if you pay tax, please select gift aid as this will give more!

THANK YOU!!!

Paula xxx

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

pageSummary: I am doing this because because I lost my mum in 2019 of November  26 and it's be
pageSummaryWhy: I lost my mum in 2019 of November  26 and it's be
story: November 25 my mum and dad are at home doing dinner and relaxing  watching  tv my brother  goes over to use there even and my mum was fine she was her normal  self  and my brother  says thank u for using there overn and goes back to my flat were I am and his girlfriend is that evening  I go to bed very late and by 1 o'clock  or 2 o'clock in the afternoon  my dad come home to blood everywhere  and my mum missing  so he calls david my brother  to see if we new anything  but he told us  we was worried  and I already  knew  it was really  bad news before we even got it so we called  about to find out and that when we found out my mum was in hospital  at st gorge in Luton but they told us something  that gave us hope when we got there she was already gone and we didn't  understand  then my dad got upset  after  the doctor  was talking  and then I said well is mum ok or has she gone my nan said she has gone and I broke down and cry so much I couldn't  breathe properly . So now you see I see things differently  now I had to change  but I wouldn't want anyone  to go though  this so that is why I want to do this

pageSummary: I am giving up chocolate for the Month of March because I want to help them to "Fix more Broken Hearts"
pageSummaryWhat: I am giving up chocolate for the Month of March
pageSummaryWhy: I want to help them to "Fix more Broken Hearts"
story:
In November1994 my niece was born with a heart defect and needed open heart surgery at 2 days old...then on 27th December 2011 my lovely mum had a massive heart attack. She was given a triple heart bypass and cared for by an amazing medical team and thankfully she lived to tell the tale. 

As you all know, I am THE BIGGEST chocoholic ever! This challenge is massive for me and will definately not be easy.

 I am doing it to raise much needed funds for the British Heart Foundation to help with research and to help to fix many more "Broken Hearts"

Please donate if you can, every penny helps. Thank you x

pageSummary: We're collecting in memory of Win Coombes
pageSummaryWhat: We're collecting in memory of Win Coombes
story:
Sadly Win Coombes died earlier this year. Due to restrictions of the pandemic, family and friends are invited to make donations in lieu of flowers.

About Guide Dogs

As a result of the latest developments, we are unable to go ahead with thousands of collections planned across the UK in the coming months. Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss across the UK.It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs.

story:
Hi,

I currently play for Leicester City Women's Football Club in the Reserves. Unfortunately, due to lockdown, we are unable to continue with our training or matches.

However, as a team, we have decided to complete a distance challenge for charity. In our team, we will be running 651 miles/1041 KM in 5 weeks. The distance has been decided as we are running a route that takes us via all the stadiums planned on being used for the Women's Euros in 2022.

The charity I have chosen is The Guide Dogs for the Blind Association. My grandfather recently passed away after being blind for 18 years. He was lucky enough to have a guide dog, which gave him the independence and confidence to go out and continue life as normally as he could. Having a guide dog kept him safe and I want to help give that opportunity to someone by helping raise money so another puppy can be trained to help someone in need. 

If you could donate, no matter how small or big, it would be hugely appreciated. If you can't donate, please don't worry. Hopefully, you can help spread our challenge instead.

Thanks,

Monique

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
In the UK today, almost two million people are living with sight loss and of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone. Many suffer from depression and struggle with feelings of isolation.

Guide Dogs is here to help solve this problem. We provide individual support that overcomes the emotional and physical challenges faced by people living with sight loss.

We work for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life. We work for a world where blind people no longer feel invisible, where the quality of their eye sight is genuinely the only difference between them and the rest of society.

A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling your needs and dreams. A world where being blind or partially sighted isn't what defines you.

eventName: One Flew Over The Cuckoos Nest
pageSummary: I am having a severe buzz
pageSummaryWhat: I am having a severe buzz
story:
Before lockdown began in 2020 I was arguably already due a haircut. But Lockdown happened and hairdressers closed.

My hair grew. I thought I would address it after lockdown. I didn’t.

Lockdown Two happened and Hairdressers closed again. My hair grew again. I thought I would address it this time after lockdown. I didn’t.

Lockdown Three has happened. As such my hair has now not been cut for over a year and it is now a halfway house between that of a retired WWF wrestler and a faded glam rocker. At the back and the sides it is an unruly length.

With hairdressers not looking like they are opening again soon this situation does need addressing before I turn into cousin IT from the Adams family. This being so I have two viable options :

1/ Tie my hair back and begin wearing it in a ponytail style a la comic book guy in The Simpsons

2/ I get some clippers and ask for a DIY haircut from my daughters – though this will be a drastic shave down to a few mm all over rather than a cut.

Sad as it is I am still swaying towards 1/ as it is simply the path of least resistance and has none of the trauma or is as drastic as 2/ (apart from the severity of the buzz cut then the real fear at my age is that after cutting it so drastically nothing will actually grow back).

Though I know that sensibly 1/ is an option not open to any man over the age of 30 I still need an incentive in order to do 2/

As you all know Great Ormond Street (GOSH) is a very worthy children’s charity. So If I reach the target figure above by the end of the month then I will see this as more than an incentive and a veritable sign that I should cut (and perhaps buy a hat).

Even if you have no preference over the ridicule I open myself up to : ponytail or drastic buzz cut then this is a good easy opportunity to donate a little to a worthy cause.

I will post the results of the undoubtedly stupid action man style buzz cut on here if it takes place.

story:
The Liverpool DHM/HM’s have set them selves a challenge to do a sponsored walk in aid of fundraising for Great Ormond Street Hospital & our pledge to become more healthy in 2021! 

We will be doing the equivalent of a return journey to Scotland which is equivalent to 560 miles from Liverpool.

To do this between the 8 of us, we will each be doing at least 10k steps (5 miles) a day for 14 consecutive days to complete the challenge.

Please support us in reaching our £500 target for such an amazing charity! Thanks in advance for your generosity.

Kurtis, Bonnie, Gabby, Barbara, Clare, Bernice, Jackie & Alison.

Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Every day 619 children and young people arrive at GOSH to receive care and life saving treatments to ensure they can continue to lead healthy lives. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital.During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page to support the Sue Davis Hair & Beauty Charity Challenge.

As lockdown 3.0 starts, we thought as a team we could use our time to raise money for an amazing charity (as well as get ourselves a little fitter along the way).

Our chosen charity is Cancer Research UK. The reason we have selected them is because we have a close connection with 'My New Hair' and the 'Little Princess Trust' as we offer a wig service to people undergoing treatment for Cancer. So it's a charity that is very close to our hearts.

Collectively, the team will walk, run or ride 500km to raise £500!
Our goal is to achieve this in one month, so please make sure you contribute to this worth while cause, and keep up to date with our progress on Instagram. 

We are so excited to meet our target, but we can't do this without your support. Any donation helps, from £1 to £100, it all goes towards a fantastic cause that funds the research which can change people's lives. 

We hope you are able to contribute to Cancer Research UK. Stay safe!

- Sue & the Team x

story:
World Cancer Day - 4th February 2021

At some point in our lives we have lost someone to cancer, or know someone who went through hell but survived it. We’ve all said at some point “he/she was taken too young” or asked ourselves “why did it take them?”

We’re never going to get those answers but we can raise money so we can find a cure and hope we never have to ask those questions again.

Please donate as much or as little as you can to cancer research who work so hard, even in this difficult time during the pandemic.

Cancer may of started this fight, but we’ll finish it x

story:
After a lovely few days over Christmas, we sadly lost my wonderful husband, Barry, two days before his 57th birthday. He was so brave, living with this horrible cancer for the last 10 years. He had so much more to give. I’ll always love him and always miss him, and I hope I can live up to him and the way he held his head up in the the face of life’s unfairness.

story:
With 'Non-Elite' football suspended following latest COVID-19 restrictions, Northwich Villa Under 15's are taking on a virtual challenge visiting all their favourite football clubs. 

Starting at Hibernian FC in Edinburgh, the players will Run, Walk and Cycle 439 miles to Chelsea FC in London, visiting the Etihad Stadium, Old Trafford, Liverpool and Stoke along the way.

The club are unable to train and play matches so this is a great way to keep the lads motivated and training during Lockdown. The players will be running, cycling and walking from their homes and logging their collective miles to reach London!

It's been a tough year for junior football but Head Coach, Steve Roberts and his team (all volunteers) have kept the team busy with regular training and matches. Many matches were played behind closed doors due to restrictions but Assistant Coach, Ewan has kept the parents up-to-date with the action, posting real time updates in the parents WhatsApp Group.


The team will be raising money for 2 charities close to their heart, Cancer Research UK and St Luke's Cheshire Hospice.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
My Dad very sadly passed away recently after a short battle with cancer.

Just after Xmas he was admitted as an in-patient to the Marie Curie Hospice in Solihull for palliative care. I didn’t have any real knowledge or experience of what a hospice was like or what to expect but from the minute we arrived, I was amazed by how nice it was. Everyone has a spacious private room that looks out onto the landscaped gardens
and in Dad’s room he was fortunate enough to have a birdfeeder right outside his window which he was very happy about being an avid birdwatcher. The love, care and kindness shown by all the staff was remarkable, especially when having to work in difficult conditions due to Covid but nothing was too much trouble for them. They showed great understanding, compassion and were always there for
emotional support and made Dad’s final few days as comfortable as possible. They were truly amazing and it’s something I’ll never forget and always be grateful for.

I was surprised to learn that two-thirds of the money to run the hospice each year comes from generous donations from people, companies and trusts and the remaining third comes from the NHS.

This got me thinking of what I could do to help support the work of this amazing charity, so I’ve decided to put my own life at risk and run 100 miles in two weeks starting on Friday 15 January to try and raise as much money as possible for the hospice.

Assuming I survive, I will update you all on my progress at the halfway point and on completion.

If you would like to make a donation (no matter how large or small) it would be greatly appreciated.

Many thanks

Dave

Thank you from all of us

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

On 20th January, it will be 3 years since I lost my mum/best friend to the dreaded “C”. Anyone who knew my mum, knew she was a strong, hard working, selfless person that did everything for her family. My mum made me who I am today! My mum was always her happiest with her family and the outdoors, so I am pledging to walk 13,000 steps ( 13 is my lucky number) with my pooch Dexter daily to raise some pennies towards an an amazing charity that helped my mum, my self and my family through what was an awful time.

If you can spare even a few pennies, myself and Dexter and of course Marie curie will be extremely grateful. 

Thank you in advance and last but not least stay safe and well EVERYONE XX 🌼

pageSummary: We are inviting donations because it was Angela's wish to help others with cancer
pageSummaryWhy: it was Angela's wish to help others with cancer
story:
Our beautiful mum / grandmother / friend Angela died on 11th January 2021, just weeks after being diagnosed with cervical cancer.

Angela's heart was full of kindness and love for others, so it is typical that among her dying wishes was that money and awareness be raised for Marie Curie UK, a charity which provides care and support through terminal illness for those with cancer and their loved-ones.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Thank you for your kind generosity.

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Hi everyone This year me and my team Marie Curie are raising money for Marie Curie Hospice, Edinburgh. Not so long ago someone of us in the team lost someone in the family from cancer and our team goal is to rase much money as possible to help Marie Curie Nurses and hospices continue to provide frontline care at this unprecedented time of need.We cant say for sure how long it will be before our situation improves. We urgently need you to donate to there emergency appeal today.

Were appealing to the generosity of the public,friends and family to help them deliver there care, which is needed now more than ever.

Our hospice is a warm and welcoming place, supporting people in Edinburgh and their loved ones with expert care, every day of the year. Our doctors, nurses, physiotherapists and social workers are supported by a team of volunteers, who play a vital role in the running of the hospice.Some of the people we support stay in our in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night and stay with their loved ones if they wish to.We also support local people with clinics, therapies and activities during the day including one-to-one care, groups and things like reiki and massage. As well as people with a terminal illness, we also support carers and families with things like bereavement support groups where people can share their experiences and feelings.Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Edinburgh get the care and support they need.

Thanks 

Ryan Peter Liam

story: As a company, Boston Hale will be supporting Marie Curie over the next 12 months to help support the amazing work they do on a daily basis. Marie Curie nursing care is needed more than ever at the present time to help care for patients who can no longer be looked after in hospital. Please show your support by donating to our fundraising page. One of our key goals is to hit £8500 which is the cost of running one hospice for just one day. On January 29th we will be doing our first team fundraiser by running a joint 150km. As we are in Lockdown each member of staff will be running, walking or even rowing from their own home.

story: Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page. I will be walking 10,000 steps everyday in march for step into spring to raise money for Marie Curie to help care for families and loved ones with cancer.It costs £180 for one nurse to provide hands on care in someone's home for a full 9 hour shift.I sadly lost my daddy 26th may 2020 to cancer and saw what these nurses do and cant thank the nurses enough for what they done for my daddy and myself.I will also be doing this in my daddys memory every step I take I no my daddy will be with me I will post updates on my journey in March and hope to reach my target.

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Thank you for visiting. I have signed up to Step into Spring in memory of my Beautiful Auntie Eileen who was cared for by the Marie Curie during the end of her life. The support they give her & our family was amazing and I am forever grateful.

So to some people 10,000 steps a day may seem nothing however whilst working from home I can honestly say this will be a challenge for me! It would anyways but more so with not being able to get out as much.

Please donate anything! Even £1 is better than nothing!

Thank you :)

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all Yorkshire and the North East lifeboat stations is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. Add to that crew training and kit, and the pounds start to add up.  Since the Covid-19 pandemic, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to keep our lifeboats afloat. 
We rely on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea - your donation to this page will help support the running of our 19 stations in Yorkshire and the North East
Amble, Berwick upon Tweed, Blyth, Bridlington, Craster, Cullercoats, Filey, Flamborough, Hartlepool, Humber, Newbiggin, Redcar, Scarborough, Seahouses, Staithes and Runswick, Sunderland, Tynemouth, Whitby and Withernsea
title: RNLI's Friends of Scarborough Lifeboat
rememberedPersonSummary.name: NA
Name: RNLI's Friends of Scarborough Lifeboat

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Last year our Filey Lifeboat Day went virtual and you helped to raise £9,391.64!

After its huge success, whilst we are still unable to see you in person we are continuing our drive to raise vital funds online to support the work of the RNLI.

‘All donations made on this page will be solely restricted towards the
running costs of the RNLI Filey Lifeboat Station’.

As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.Thank you.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Our RNLI lifeboats in the East of England protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 

The stunning coastline of Essex, Suffolk, Norfolk and Lincolnshire are enjoyed by millions of people from across the country every year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 17 of the lifeboat stations in East of England is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Tower Lifeboat Station, consistently the busiest in the RNLI's 238-station network, patrols the River Thames at peak times and during large events including New Year and other festivities.  It works closely with the other emergency services, gives first aid to passengers on riverboats, provides water safety information and assists with suicide prevention.

The River Thames is unpredictable and catches people out.  In 2019 Tower's lifeboats were called out 552 times and saved 22 lives.  Many of those rescued had no idea they would ever need help - office workers, tourists, local residents - not just people in boats.  The station has remained on duty 24/7 since the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic, adapting its strategies to remain COVID secure and saving lives.

Any donation you make will support the RNLI's Tower Appeal and make a vital contribution to people's lives and safety on and around the River Thames.

You can find out more at https://www.towerrnli.com

pageSummary: Raising money in memory of Phil Jones because he loved Filey and always supported the lifeboat
pageSummaryWhat: Raising money in memory of Phil Jones
pageSummaryWhy: he loved Filey and always supported the lifeboat
story:
Phil Jones died on 4 January 2021 aged 89. 

As children we always went to Filey on holiday and were always there for lifeboat day.  We would hear the maroons go off and saw the boats launch in all weathers, crewed by volunteers to save lives at sea.  

In recent years we have visited with our own children and our parents came too.  Fabulous holidays with 3 generations.

Phil loved Filey and always supported the lifeboats, his wife Jean has asked that donations in his memory be made to the RNLI Filey Lifeboat. 

Thanks so much

Annette & Gareth

pageSummary: I am running London Landmarks Half Marathon 2021 because our planet needs our help
pageSummaryWhat: I am running London Landmarks Half Marathon 2021
story:
2021 is the start of a vital decade for nature and for our planet. 

I have been lucky enough to travel with my family and see first hand beautiful endangered wildlife in their natural habitat, elephants, leopards, bears, rhinos to name a few. I want future generations to be able to do the same. 

Every donation goes towards different projects around the world to restore nature and protect wildlife. 

This is the year that we ramp up our ambition and our action, build on the progress we’ve made, and start to truly turn things around. We will look back on this year as a turning point. By 2030, nature and wildlife could be recovering all around us. 

"Our mission is to create a world where people and wildlife can thrive together"WWF

525 my target amount is the number of months I've been walking this incredible planet. Please help me raise this amount whilst running my 2nd Half marathon.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity.

pageSummary: I am fundraising because our planet and wildlife needs preserving.
pageSummaryWhy: our planet and wildlife needs preserving.
story:
Some of us may have felt helpless during the past year, trying to find ways to give back. Whether that’s through volunteering, supporting key workers or just being there for someone in need. I take inspiration from my friends who have opted out of gifts this year, in favour of donations, to a cause close to them. 

That is why, on behalf of my birthday this year, I want to spread awareness and help fundraise for the WWF. Many of you who know me, know that I’m passionate about wildlife and sustaining the planet we live on for all species. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

pageSummary: OH MY GOD, I've signed up for a marathon because i must be crazy. But all for a good cause.
pageSummaryWhat: OH MY GOD, I've signed up for a marathon
pageSummaryWhy: i must be crazy. But all for a good cause.
story:
Oh dear, 

What am i thinking, 

I have decided it would be a good idea for a new goal this year. 

At the start of lock down i started running,  I've always said i hated running and would never do it but must admit i was enjoying it.

So with maybe a bit of convincing from a friend i thought time to go big or go home.

An important point for me is to do it for a good cause ( as this make it harder to quit) 

As most of you know nature and the living planet is important to me and the work the WWF does is amazing to help this cause.

 The  WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

Please support me doing this and enjoy watching me put myself though this pain.

pageSummary: I am trekking because our home – planet Earth – is perishing fast
pageSummaryWhy: our home – planet Earth – is perishing fast
story:
Our planet is in crisis – from climate change to the pollution in our oceans and devastation of our forests.

A serious change needs to happen now, and every little helps. I just want to play a role in being part of the solution.

To take part in this 106km around the Isle of Wight, I need to raise at least £595.

Anything you can donate would be greatly appreciated.

Thank you.

charity.name: Oxfam
story:
My team of 4 have just under 9 months to train for a 100K walk through the South Downs. We will stop for food but will have to push on through the night if we want to make it in under 30 hours.

Sponsor us as little or as much as you can to help our enthusiasm through this trail.  Trailwalker UK supports the incredible work of both Oxfam Great Britain and The Gurkha Welfare Trust.

charity.name: Oxfam
story: Trailwalker is the ultimate team endurance event. The challenge is to walk, jog or run 100km non-stop across the South Downs Way in under 30 hours in a team of four, with a support crew of two members to help you get to the finish line. As you train, trek and fundraise for Trailwalker 2020, you will be helping to end poverty around the world. The money you raise will support both the work of Oxfam as well as the Gurkha Welfare Trust.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Thank you for your sponsor, it really means a lot!!

OVER 12 MILLION CHILDREN IN YEMEN WERE ALREADY IN DANGER FROM WAR, DISEASE AND HUNGER. NOW CORONAVIRUS THREATENS THEIR LITTLE LIVES TOO!We would like to raise money for Unicef's Yemen Crisis Appeal, just £33 provides a child with food for 3 weeks!🚶‍♂️Our aim is to collectively (as a team along with our clients) travel the distance from Bedford to Yemen which is 3670 miles by 1st March and raise £5000 along the way!🚴‍♀️This will be done by walking, running, cycling, rowing or skiing, you name it! on a daily basis! Every little helps here, every mile counts! Not only is it a great cause to be involved in but we also feel it provides us all with something positive to focus on, accountability, community and a reason to be as active as possible during this challenging time we find ourselves in!Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.We cannot thank you enough for your kind donation!! https://vimeo.com/499120007

Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity. We cannot thank you enough for your kind donation!! https://vimeo.com/499120007

charity.description: CARE International is one of the world’s leading aid agencies working in over 80 countries around the globe. We seek a world of hope, tolerance and social justice, with  women and girls at the centre, where poverty has been overcome, and people live with equal opportunities in security and dignity.
charity.name: CARE International UK
eventName: LCFC Women Res & U18 Lockdown Run
story:
After five years of conflict, most of the population in Yemen needs humanitarian assistance. They have a lack of basic healthcare, severe food shortages and limited clean water.  

CARE is focused on helping the most vulnerable people, through distributing food to families in need, and cash vouchers so that families can purchase for themselves the food they need.

Over a year of fighting and fuel shortages has destroyed water pipes and water pumping facilities, so CARE is rehabilitating water sources and providing water tanks so women and children can get safe drinking water without having to travel long distances.

CARE is also providing hygiene kits, paying special attention to womens and children's needs.

Thank you for reading. For more information please visit the dedicated Yemen Crisis page on CARE's website: www.careinternational.org.uk/emergencies/yemen-crisis
